"Normocytic Anemia"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_hm_s10_1",
"title":{
"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"a3f35a",
"children":[
"Normocytic anemia is associated with a normal ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"mean corpuscular volume",
"children":[
"MCV"
]
},
" of 80 to 100 fL. The reticulocyte count can help differentiate the cause."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"966e8f",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Increased reticulocyte count:"
]
},
" Normocytic anemia with an increased absolute reticulocyte count (>100,000/Î¼L) reflects either erythrocyte loss (bleeding or hemolysis) or response to therapy (iron, folate, or cobalamin)."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"69c096",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Decreased reticulocyte count:"
]
},
" Normocytic anemia with a lower than expected reticulocyte count indicates underproduction anemia:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"fa2df7",
"children":[
"inflammation with deficient erythropoietin (",
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"most frequent cause"
]
},
")"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"e58d93",
"children":[
"nutritional deficiencies (iron, folate, cobalamin)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"4d624f",
"children":[
"hypometabolism (hypothyroidism, testosterone deficiency)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"cc63dc",
"children":[
"a primary hematopoietic disorder (pure red cell aplasia or myelodysplasia)"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"ef25ac",
"children":[
"Anemia from iron deficiency and inflammation are often confused (see Study Table). ",
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"A serum ferritin level >100 ng/mL rules out iron deficiency."
]
}
]
},
